<subSubSection id="C3012AA0FA3DFF85FF71FB02FE199236" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA4792BFA3DFF85FF71FB02FE8A903E" blockId="28.[151,424,1230,1289]" box="[151,330,1265,1289]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
(
<figureCitation id="132065AEFA3DFF85FF79FB02FE81903E" box="[159,321,1265,1289]" captionStart="FIGURES 104–115" captionStartId="30.[151,263,1822,1845]" captionTargetBox="[162,1426,201,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-94@30.[151,1436,193,1801]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 104–115. Thrips species. T. flavus, female 104–106: (104) Head &amp; pronotum; (105) Antenna, right; (106). Metascutum. T. flavus, male 107–108: (107) Tergites VIII–IX, sculpture omitted: (108) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. floreus, female 109–115: (109) Head &amp; pronotum; (110) Antenna, right; (111) Mesonotum &amp; metascutum; (112) Tergite V &amp; pleurotergite, right side; (113) Tergites VIII–X. T. floreus, male 114–115: (114) Tergites VIII–IX; (115) Sternite VI." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Figs. 104–108</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA4792BFA3DFF85FF71FACAFD469346" blockId="28.[151,1437,1337,1937]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B96FA539FA3DFF85FF71FACAFEB49066" box="[151,372,1337,1361]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Female macroptera</emphasis>
. Body including legs uniformly yellow; antennal segments I to II yellow, III to IV brown often with basal half pale, V yellow with distal third brown, VI brown often with basal fourth pale; VII to VIII brown; fore wings uniformly pale. Ocellar setae III just behind fore ocellus (
<figureCitation id="132065AEFA3DFF85FC2CFA72FBF190AE" box="[970,1073,1409,1433]" captionStart="FIGURES 104–115" captionStartId="30.[151,263,1822,1845]" captionTargetBox="[162,1426,201,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-94@30.[151,1436,193,1801]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 104–115. Thrips species. T. flavus, female 104–106: (104) Head &amp; pronotum; (105) Antenna, right; (106). Metascutum. T. flavus, male 107–108: (107) Tergites VIII–IX, sculpture omitted: (108) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. floreus, female 109–115: (109) Head &amp; pronotum; (110) Antenna, right; (111) Mesonotum &amp; metascutum; (112) Tergite V &amp; pleurotergite, right side; (113) Tergites VIII–X. T. floreus, male 114–115: (114) Tergites VIII–IX; (115) Sternite VI." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 104</figureCitation>
). Antennae (
<figureCitation id="132065AEFA3DFF85FB21FA72FAEB90AE" box="[1223,1323,1409,1433]" captionStart="FIGURES 104–115" captionStartId="30.[151,263,1822,1845]" captionTargetBox="[162,1426,201,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-94@30.[151,1436,193,1801]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 104–115. Thrips species. T. flavus, female 104–106: (104) Head &amp; pronotum; (105) Antenna, right; (106). Metascutum. T. flavus, male 107–108: (107) Tergites VIII–IX, sculpture omitted: (108) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. floreus, female 109–115: (109) Head &amp; pronotum; (110) Antenna, right; (111) Mesonotum &amp; metascutum; (112) Tergite V &amp; pleurotergite, right side; (113) Tergites VIII–X. T. floreus, male 114–115: (114) Tergites VIII–IX; (115) Sternite VI." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 105</figureCitation>
) 7- or 8- segmented. Metascutum (
<figureCitation id="132065AEFA3DFF85FE53FA56FDD4908A" box="[437,532,1445,1469]" captionStart="FIGURES 104–115" captionStartId="30.[151,263,1822,1845]" captionTargetBox="[162,1426,201,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-94@30.[151,1436,193,1801]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 104–115. Thrips species. T. flavus, female 104–106: (104) Head &amp; pronotum; (105) Antenna, right; (106). Metascutum. T. flavus, male 107–108: (107) Tergites VIII–IX, sculpture omitted: (108) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. floreus, female 109–115: (109) Head &amp; pronotum; (110) Antenna, right; (111) Mesonotum &amp; metascutum; (112) Tergite V &amp; pleurotergite, right side; (113) Tergites VIII–X. T. floreus, male 114–115: (114) Tergites VIII–IX; (115) Sternite VI." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 106</figureCitation>
) sculptured with longitudinal anastomosing striae except anteromedially, lines of sculpture not convergent to middle at posterior margin; median pair of setae far from anterior margin; CPS present. Fore wing first vein with seven basal and three distal setae. Abdominal tergites II with 4 lateral marginal setae; tergite VIII with posteromarginal comb complete; tergite IX with 2 pairs of CPS; sternites without discal setae; sternite I without microsetae anteromedially; sternite VII with S1 setae far from posterior margin; pleurotergites without discal setae and ciliate microtrichia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA4792BFA3DFF85FF21F98EFE199236" blockId="28.[151,1437,1337,1937]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B96FA539FA3DFF85FF21F98EFE4B93A2" box="[199,395,1661,1685]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Male macroptera</emphasis>
. Body colour same as female. Antennal segment VI with more 20 setae. Abdominal tergite VIII (
<figureCitation id="132065AEFA3DFF85FF3EF952FEF0938E" box="[216,304,1697,1721]" captionStart="FIGURES 104–115" captionStartId="30.[151,263,1822,1845]" captionTargetBox="[162,1426,201,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-94@30.[151,1436,193,1801]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 104–115. Thrips species. T. flavus, female 104–106: (104) Head &amp; pronotum; (105) Antenna, right; (106). Metascutum. T. flavus, male 107–108: (107) Tergites VIII–IX, sculpture omitted: (108) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. floreus, female 109–115: (109) Head &amp; pronotum; (110) Antenna, right; (111) Mesonotum &amp; metascutum; (112) Tergite V &amp; pleurotergite, right side; (113) Tergites VIII–X. T. floreus, male 114–115: (114) Tergites VIII–IX; (115) Sternite VI." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig.107</figureCitation>
) with a few posteromarginal comb medially; tergite IX with S1 setae slightly ahead of level of S2 setae and subequal length to S2 setae, slightly closer to S2 setae than each other; sternites III to VII each with an oblong pore plate (
<figureCitation id="132065AEFA3DFF85FE8CF91AFE0C9236" box="[362,460,1769,1793]" captionStart="FIGURES 104–115" captionStartId="30.[151,263,1822,1845]" captionTargetBox="[162,1426,201,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-94@30.[151,1436,193,1801]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 104–115. Thrips species. T. flavus, female 104–106: (104) Head &amp; pronotum; (105) Antenna, right; (106). Metascutum. T. flavus, male 107–108: (107) Tergites VIII–IX, sculpture omitted: (108) Sternite VII, sculpture omitted. T. floreus, female 109–115: (109) Head &amp; pronotum; (110) Antenna, right; (111) Mesonotum &amp; metascutum; (112) Tergite V &amp; pleurotergite, right side; (113) Tergites VIII–X. T. floreus, male 114–115: (114) Tergites VIII–IX; (115) Sternite VI." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3012AA0FA3DFF85FF21F8FEFED092A6" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA4792BFA3DFF85FF21F8FEFED092A6" blockId="28.[151,1437,1337,1937]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B96FA539FA3DFF85FF21F8FEFE889211" bold="true" box="[199,328,1805,1830]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Comments</emphasis>
. 
<materialsCitation id="3B737376FA3DFF85FEBAF8FEFECC92A6" collectionCode="III" country="Japan" county="This" location="It" municipality="Palearctic region" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Hokkaido">
<collectingCounty id="62C501A7FA3DFF85FEBAF8FEFE4E9212" box="[348,398,1805,1829]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">This</collectingCounty>
species is the most abundant flower-living species in 
<collectingCountry id="F30C39BBFA3DFF85FBC3F8FDFBA59212" box="[1061,1125,1806,1829]" name="Japan" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Japan</collectingCountry>
and is widespread in the 
<collectingMunicipality id="6BC0E351FA3DFF85FF71F8C2FE97927E" box="[151,343,1841,1865]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Palearctic region</collectingMunicipality>
. 
<location id="8EC42FF0FA3DFF85FE87F8C1FEB2927E" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03B2C83DFA3DFF85FF71FB3DFED092A6:8EC42FF0FA3DFF85FE87F8C1FEB2927E" box="[353,370,1842,1865]" country="Japan" county="This" municipality="Palearctic region" name="It" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" stateProvince="Hokkaido">It</location>
can be found on many kinds of plants from 
<collectingRegion id="49DFB7C9FA3DFF85FCBBF8C2FC0B927E" box="[861,971,1841,1865]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
to 
<location id="8EC42FF0FA3DFF85FC08F8C2FB85927E" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03B2C83DFA3DFF85FF71FB3DFED092A6:8EC42FF0FA3DFF85FC08F8C2FB85927E" box="[1006,1093,1841,1865]" country="Japan" county="This" municipality="Palearctic region" name="Kyushu" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" stateProvince="Hokkaido">Kyushu</location>
and Shikoku. This species can be distinguished relatively easily from other members of the genus by the position of ocellar setae 
<collectionCode id="ED0AE1EEFA3DFF85FB0CF8A5FAC6925A" box="[1258,1286,1878,1901]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">III</collectionCode>
and antennal coloration
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
